<font color="#FF0000">LATE RESPONSE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Nov 15 23:02:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chopper pilots were ...<br><br>
Chopper pilots were my heroes -- along with medics and nurses.<br><br>
Ed -- good post.  I needed a while to think about it.<br><br>
The memories of the first half of my tour are vivid and strong.  Richard, Rodney and John all died in Operation Cedar Falls, a few months after I arrived.  The memories during the second half are more of a blur.  Many of the names escape me.  I can remember how they died, but the &quot;pictures&quot; aren't there.  Maybe that is better -- for me anyway.<br><br>
Richard was one of my heroes.  He was admired by others as well.  Two of us have visited him family in Sacremento, California.  I held his crying sister in my arms and said &quot;your brother was a helluva man.&quot;  I wish I could have done more, but I didn't know what else I could do.<br><br>
The war is thirty years old for me.  Many of my polarized feelings have melded together.  I feel most sad for the families left without their loved ones -- the parents who raised the children and watched them grow to lose them so quickly.  I don't know what I could say to alleviate their sorrows.  &quot;Your sons and daughters were and are loved and admired by those who knew them.,&quot; are the best words that I can come up with.  &quot;Blend pride with sorrow -- feel proud, and remember them with kindness.&quot;  Know matter what I say, I feel my words come up short.<br><br>
I have days when I think of life as little more than absurd.  I have seen  broken hearts and battered spirits and I wonder why.  And yet, I have seen acts of kindness -- hands on shoulders, words of support and smiles to reinforce wills to continue with personal struggles. I have cursed God and laughed at fate both mine and yours.<br><br>
And I have laughed as you and I have bantered back and forth over who is &quot;Mom's true favorite.&quot;<br><br>
But there is something I do &quot;see.&quot;  Life on the planet is getting better.  I'm impressed with many of the young and we are all evolving to better places.  It will never be as fast as we wish, but we are progressing.<br><br>
Paul
